{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567745"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:06:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:06:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19323"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19323"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.05,0.59,0.04,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12057"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104290"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12057"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19323"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86624"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4958"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"11466"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12918"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28415"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30658"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104290"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic reporting increasing work-related stress over the past three months. She is a junior doctor working in a busy Emergency Department. She describes feeling emotionally drained, cynical about her work, and questions her career choice. She has started calling in sick more frequently and finds it difficult to empathise with patients. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She lives alone and has recently stopped attending her usual social activities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears tired with vital signs within normal limits. She becomes tearful when discussing her work situation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management strategy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cognitive behavioural therapy","Change to part-time work hours","Structured professional counseling","Prescription for selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor","Extended sick leave"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents classic features of professional burnout, characterized by emotional exhaustion, depersonalization (cynicism towards patients), and reduced sense of personal accomplishment. The symptoms have developed gradually and are specifically related to work stress rather than suggesting a primary mental health condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStructured professional counseling\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial step as it provides a safe space to explore contributing factors, develop coping strategies, and create an action plan for addressing workplace stressors. Professional counseling can help identify specific triggers and teach stress management techniques while allowing the doctor to continue working.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECognitive behavioural therapy\u003C/strong\u003E may be helpful as part of a comprehensive approach to managing burnout, particularly if negative thought patterns are contributing to the stress. However, it is not the most appropriate initial management strategy as it focuses on changing thought patterns rather than addressing the immediate workplace stressors and providing broader support that professional counseling offers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStarting a \u003Cstrong\u003Eselective serotonin reuptake inhibitor\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as the first step, as this presentation is primarily related to workplace stress rather than clinical depression. While there may be overlap between burnout and depression, addressing workplace factors through counseling should be the initial approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtended sick leave\u003C/strong\u003E might temporarily reduce stress but doesn\u0027t address the underlying causes of burnout. It could also lead to increased anxiety about returning to work and doesn\u0027t provide the tools needed for long-term coping.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChanging to \u003Cstrong\u003Epart-time work hours\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered as part of a longer-term strategy, but should not be the first step before exploring other interventions. This option might also have significant financial and career implications that need careful consideration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevention of burnout includes maintaining clear work-life boundaries, regular exercise, peer support groups, and effective time management. Regular clinical supervision and mentor support are also valuable protective factors for healthcare professionals.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Burnout is characterized by emotional exhaustion, depersonalization, and reduced personal accomplishment.","Regular exercise, maintaining work-life boundaries, and seeking peer support are effective strategies for preventing burnout.","Professional counseling should be sought when burnout symptoms significantly impact work performance or personal life."],"references":["West CP, Dyrbye LN, Erwin PJ, Shanafelt TD. Interventions to prevent and reduce physician burnout: a systematic review and meta-analysis. Lancet. 2016;388(10057):2272-2281. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0140673616312786","Regehr C, Glancy D, Pitts A, LeBlanc VR. Interventions to reduce the consequences of stress in physicians: a review and meta-analysis. J Nerv Ment Dis. 2014;202(5):353-359. Available at: https://journals.lww.com/jonmd/Abstract/2014/05000/Interventions_to_Reduce_the_Consequences_of.4.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86624"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19323"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86624"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-31T12:00:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-31T12:00:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12057"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104290"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt"